        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As an elementary-school substitute teacher in New York City this year, I disagree with the assertion of the domestic violence consultant interviewed by Brent Staples (Editorial Observer, June 26) that harassment against girls is tolerated in the schoolyard.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As an elementary-school substitute teacher in New York City this year, I disagree with the assertion of the domestic violence consultant interviewed by Brent Staples (Editorial Observer, June 26) that harassment against girls is tolerated in the schoolyard.</p>
        <p>In the more than 60 classrooms I have been in this year in District 30 in Queens, every single one has had  rules prominently posted about students' respecting each other and keeping their hands and feet to themselves. In fact, the children are so aware of these rules that throughout the day they come up to me and other teachers to report infractions. They expect, and rightfully so, that I, the other teachers or the school administration will take disciplinary action against those who have harassed them. These actions have ranged from admonishment of the rule-breaker to suspension.</p>
        <p>JUDITH NATKINS  Jackson Heights, Queens  June 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
